1
00:04:57,474 --> 00:05:00,602
What the hell?

2
00:05:06,550 --> 00:05:08,450
Hey.

3
00:05:13,524 --> 00:05:16,982
<i>You know which side of the border you're on?</i>

4
00:05:17,094 --> 00:05:19,528
<i>You got a name, boy?</i>

5
00:05:20,764 --> 00:05:23,460
Guess...

6
00:05:23,567 --> 00:05:26,434
somethin' must have
cut your tongue off.

7
00:05:28,672 --> 00:05:30,640
Either that, or...

8
00:05:32,743 --> 00:05:37,612
you've got somethin'... to hide.

9
00:05:37,715 --> 00:05:41,378
Ah.

10
00:05:41,485 --> 00:05:43,385
Never can tell.

11
00:05:46,190 --> 00:05:50,126
You hear me plain enough.

12
00:05:54,531 --> 00:05:56,431
Ah.

13
00:05:58,736 --> 00:06:00,727
"Walter R. Henderson."

14
00:06:03,407 --> 00:06:05,534
<i>Now, I want to ask you</i>
<i>one last question.</i>

15
00:06:07,845 --> 00:06:10,837
You see this here card?

16
00:06:10,948 --> 00:06:12,916
Is it you?

17
00:06:14,218 --> 00:06:16,914
Or a relative of yours?

18
00:06:19,156 --> 00:06:22,489
Well, I'm gonna call up this number...

19
00:06:22,593 --> 00:06:26,085
and see if they can tell me who you are.

20
00:06:26,196 --> 00:06:30,155
I ain't got beds enough
to be puttin' up mutes.

21
00:06:37,875 --> 00:06:41,538
<i>Operator, I need a line out, please.</i>

22
00:06:43,881 --> 00:06:46,816
<i>Los Angeles, California.</i>

23
00:06:46,917 --> 00:06:48,885
<i>Area code--</i>

24
00:06:56,927 --> 00:06:59,418
Uh, what?

25
00:06:59,530 --> 00:07:03,694
Well, can you -- Can you tell me the exact
location of your hospital down there?

26
00:07:05,402 --> 00:07:07,734
Uh, where the hell's that?

27
00:07:09,573 --> 00:07:12,508
Oh, okay. All right.
Yeah, um --

28
00:07:12,609 --> 00:07:15,442
Okay, I'll be there.
I'll get there as fast as I can.

29
00:07:15,546 --> 00:07:19,073
Just --Will you tell him
that I'm coming, okay? Okay.

30
00:07:24,855 --> 00:07:27,551
Steven, I think you will have to change that.

31
00:07:27,658 --> 00:07:28,625
This section right here?

32
00:07:28,725 --> 00:07:30,454
Yeah, because it's in the copy.

33
00:07:30,561 --> 00:07:33,086
<i>Anne, honey?</i>

34
00:07:33,197 --> 00:07:37,065
<i>- I just got the strangest phone call.</i>
- Who from?

35
00:07:37,167 --> 00:07:41,103
From some hospital in South Texas --
a place called Terlingua.

36
00:07:42,706 --> 00:07:44,606
They say they found Travis.

37
00:07:44,708 --> 00:07:46,539
Oh, no.

38
00:07:46,643 --> 00:07:49,043
What are you going to do?

39
00:07:49,146 --> 00:07:52,377
- Well, I'll go down and-and get him.
- Oh, Walt.

40
00:07:52,483 --> 00:07:54,951
What am I gonna do?
I can't leave him down there.

41
00:07:58,722 --> 00:08:00,519
What about Hunter?

42
00:08:00,624 --> 00:08:02,649
What am I supposed to tell him?

43
00:08:02,759 --> 00:08:06,251
Uh, well, just tell him
I had to go on a business trip.

44
00:08:06,363 --> 00:08:08,388
I mean about Travis.

45
00:08:14,271 --> 00:08:16,501
Well.

46
00:08:16,607 --> 00:08:18,905
I guess you better
tell him the truth.

47
00:08:40,163 --> 00:08:42,028
10 to Van Horn.

48
00:08:42,132 --> 00:08:44,566
90... to Alpine.

49
00:08:44,668 --> 00:08:46,568
118 south.

50
00:08:48,639 --> 00:08:50,539
Terlingua.

51
00:09:21,171 --> 00:09:23,366
You must be the brother of the mute.

52
00:09:24,908 --> 00:09:26,808
- Mute?
<i>- Ja.</i>

53
00:09:27,978 --> 00:09:31,379
They couldn't squeeze
the time of day out of him.

54
00:09:33,050 --> 00:09:35,712
Must be in a kind of jam, huh?

55
00:09:37,187 --> 00:09:39,655
I don't know.
I haven't seen him in over four years.

56
00:09:40,691 --> 00:09:42,784
Is that right?

57
00:09:42,893 --> 00:09:47,262
Well, a lot can happen to a man
in four years, I guess.

58
00:09:48,298 --> 00:09:52,291
All kinds of trouble -- expensive trouble.

59
00:09:52,402 --> 00:09:54,165
What do you mean?

60
00:09:54,271 --> 00:09:56,296
<i>Well, down here...</i>

61
00:09:56,406 --> 00:09:59,375
a man gets himself
into a fix sometimes.

62
00:09:59,476 --> 00:10:02,377
<i>And it costs a little to get him out.</i>

63
00:10:02,479 --> 00:10:04,447
You understand what I mean.

64
00:10:05,515 --> 00:10:07,949
I don't understand you.

65
00:10:08,051 --> 00:10:10,884
I wish you'd get to the point,
'cause I'd like to see my brother.

66
00:10:13,023 --> 00:10:14,923
All right, sir.

67
00:10:15,025 --> 00:10:18,324
<i>But first I would like</i>
<i>to ask you something.</i>

68
00:10:18,428 --> 00:10:22,660
Did your brother ever get hisself
into a car wreck?

69
00:10:26,470 --> 00:10:30,270
Uh, car wreck.
No, uh, not that I know of.

70
00:10:30,374 --> 00:10:34,538
<i>Then he must be mixing</i>
<i>with some hard company.</i>

71
00:10:34,645 --> 00:10:39,048
I'd like to see my brother now,
if you don't mind.

72
00:10:40,450 --> 00:10:44,045
- He disappeared.
- You mean he's not here?

73
00:10:44,154 --> 00:10:46,054
After I came all this way?

74
00:10:46,156 --> 00:10:49,455
He's been gone since early this morning.

75
00:10:50,927 --> 00:10:54,226
<i>We have his possessions nevertheless.</i>

76
00:10:54,331 --> 00:10:57,767
Saved them.

77
00:10:57,868 --> 00:11:00,200
We'd be glad to turn 'em over to you...

78
00:11:00,303 --> 00:11:04,967
<i>as soon as you take care</i>
<i>of our little reward.</i>

79
00:12:38,168 --> 00:12:39,635
Travis?

80
00:12:42,672 --> 00:12:44,640
Travis. Hey.

81
00:12:48,411 --> 00:12:50,879
Don't you recognize me?
It's Walt.

82
00:12:58,655 --> 00:13:00,555
It's your brother--Walt.

83
00:13:18,575 --> 00:13:22,944
What the hell happened to you anyway?
You look like 40 miles of rough road.

84
00:13:33,824 --> 00:13:35,917
Come on. Let's get in the car. Trav?

85
00:13:37,627 --> 00:13:39,527
Come on.

86
00:13:42,032 --> 00:13:43,932
Yeah.

87
00:13:49,005 --> 00:13:50,905
Come on.

88
00:14:31,681 --> 00:14:33,945
Here, Trav. Here's your stuff.

89
00:14:35,986 --> 00:14:37,954
I got that back at that clinic back there.

90
00:14:39,890 --> 00:14:43,883
Sure picked a hell of a spot to land in.
I don't blame you for running out of it.

91
00:14:48,965 --> 00:14:52,128
Um, look, Trav...

92
00:14:52,235 --> 00:14:54,669
we got quite a bit of travelin' to do here.

93
00:14:54,771 --> 00:14:57,069
You're not gonna clam up
the whole way, are you?

94
00:14:58,341 --> 00:15:00,036
I mean, it'll get kind of lonely.

95
00:15:04,581 --> 00:15:06,549
Trav?

96
00:15:08,118 --> 00:15:12,020
Would you mind telling me where you
disappeared to for the last four years?

97
00:15:17,260 --> 00:15:19,626
Uh, have you seen Jane or talked to her?

98
00:15:22,766 --> 00:15:25,963
<i>Gee, Anne and I, we sort of gave up on you.</i>

99
00:15:26,069 --> 00:15:29,869
We actually--
We thought you were dead, boy.

100
00:16:06,209 --> 00:16:08,109
It's pretty, uh --

101
00:16:19,055 --> 00:16:21,023
Okay.

102
00:16:29,299 --> 00:16:31,290
Well --

103
00:16:31,401 --> 00:16:33,596
Yeah.

104
00:16:35,739 --> 00:16:38,537
Well, gee, Trav,
maybe you wanna get cleaned up...

105
00:16:38,641 --> 00:16:40,802
you know, take a shower or something?

106
00:16:40,910 --> 00:16:44,107
Um, I think I'll go back into town
and get you some new clothes.

107
00:16:44,214 --> 00:16:46,205
You could use a new set of clothes,
couldn't you?

108
00:16:48,385 --> 00:16:50,285
Wh-What size shoes you wear?

109
00:16:51,988 --> 00:16:54,149
Right. We'll see.

110
00:16:58,028 --> 00:16:59,928
I'm probably one size bigger, huh?

111
00:17:02,365 --> 00:17:05,198
So, where'd you find that beard?

112
00:17:05,301 --> 00:17:08,429
It's pretty snazzy.

113
00:17:10,707 --> 00:17:13,938
Okay. I'll zip into town
and zip right back.

114
00:17:15,445 --> 00:17:17,345
I won't be gone long.

115
00:17:24,654 --> 00:17:27,088
You'll be okay, won't you, Trav?

116
00:17:29,626 --> 00:17:32,186
Yeah, I'll -- I'll be right back.

117
00:19:23,806 --> 00:19:25,774
Damn it.

118
00:20:23,633 --> 00:20:26,693
You mind telling me
where you're headed, Trav?

119
00:20:30,273 --> 00:20:32,537
What's out there?

120
00:20:38,581 --> 00:20:40,549
There's nothin' out there.

121
00:20:43,152 --> 00:20:45,120
Don't you trust me or somethin'? Huh?

122
00:20:48,758 --> 00:20:51,750
I'm just trying to help you, Trav.
That's all.

123
00:20:57,000 --> 00:20:59,161
Now come on. It's all right.

124
00:20:59,269 --> 00:21:02,466
Come on with me in the car. Huh?

125
00:22:08,204 --> 00:22:11,105
Kind of feels good
to be in new clothes, huh?

126
00:22:34,097 --> 00:22:36,964
- Hello.
- Hi. Hunter? It's Daddy.

127
00:22:38,000 --> 00:22:41,731
- I thought you'd be in bed already.
- I'm watching TV.

128
00:22:41,838 --> 00:22:45,069
Guess who I'm visiting here in Texas.

129
00:22:46,175 --> 00:22:49,235
- Who?
- Your father.

130
00:22:49,345 --> 00:22:51,313
Do you remember your father?

131
00:22:52,648 --> 00:22:54,980
<i>- No.</i>
<i>- Not at all?</i>

132
00:22:55,084 --> 00:22:57,917
<i>I remember he was kind of skinny.</i>

133
00:22:58,020 --> 00:23:01,114
<i>- He was?</i>
<i>- I think he was.</i>

134
00:23:01,224 --> 00:23:03,988
<i>- Well, guess what.</i>
<i>-I don't know.</i>

135
00:23:04,093 --> 00:23:06,186
<i>I'm gonna bring him home to visit.</i>

136
00:23:21,043 --> 00:23:22,943
Travis.

137
00:23:25,348 --> 00:23:28,977
Do you remember your little boy? Hunter.

138
00:23:31,988 --> 00:23:34,354
<i>Well, he's with us.</i>

139
00:23:34,457 --> 00:23:37,722
<i>He's been living with Anne and me</i>
<i>ever since you disappeared.</i>

140
00:23:39,495 --> 00:23:43,226
We didn't know what else to do,
so we just kept him.

141
00:23:45,334 --> 00:23:47,734
<i>One day, he was just standing at the door.</i>

142
00:23:48,771 --> 00:23:52,832
All he could tell us was that
someone brought him there in a car.

143
00:23:54,143 --> 00:23:56,907
<i>He didn't know</i>
<i>what had happened to you or Jane.</i>

144
00:23:58,147 --> 00:24:01,878
<i>We tried everything we could think of</i>
<i>to find you or Jane.</i>

145
00:24:01,984 --> 00:24:04,111
<i>We tried to locate her.</i>
<i>She'd vanished too.</i>

146
00:24:05,521 --> 00:24:07,682
We didn't know what else to do.

147
00:24:13,095 --> 00:24:15,154
<i>Travis...</i>

148
00:24:15,264 --> 00:24:17,391
<i>I don't know</i>
<i>what kind of trouble you got into.</i>

149
00:24:18,835 --> 00:24:20,860
<i>I don't know what happened.</i>

150
00:24:22,338 --> 00:24:24,966
But, damn it, I'm your brother, man.

151
00:24:26,642 --> 00:24:28,667
You can talk to me.

152
00:24:32,014 --> 00:24:34,107
<i>I’m tired of doing all the talking.</i>

153
00:25:17,593 --> 00:25:19,493
Fill it with unleaded, please.

154
00:25:22,031 --> 00:25:24,431
You know, I'm gettin' a little sick
of this silence routine.

155
00:25:24,534 --> 00:25:27,594
You can talk.

156
00:25:36,646 --> 00:25:38,773
I can be silent too, you know.

157
00:25:41,918 --> 00:25:44,478
I'd just as soon that both of us keep our mouths
shut for the whole rest of the trip.

158
00:25:44,587 --> 00:25:47,681
<i>- Paris.</i>
- You know --What?

159
00:25:49,625 --> 00:25:51,593
Paris.

160
00:25:56,265 --> 00:25:58,165
Paris?

161
00:25:58,267 --> 00:25:59,928
Paris?

162
00:26:01,737 --> 00:26:04,262
Did you ever go to Paris?

163
00:26:05,408 --> 00:26:09,174
- No.
- Could we go there now?

164
00:26:11,614 --> 00:26:13,514
It's a little out of the way.

165
00:26:16,919 --> 00:26:19,683
<i>Uh, no, I've never even been to Europe.</i>

166
00:26:19,789 --> 00:26:21,916
<i>Anne keeps wanting to go there.</i>

167
00:26:22,024 --> 00:26:24,117
<i>'Cause, well, she's from France,</i>
<i>you remember?</i>

168
00:26:25,361 --> 00:26:29,354
<i>But we never seem to find the time</i>
<i>'cause my company keeps me kind of busy.</i>

169
00:26:44,647 --> 00:26:46,615
Let's go, Trav.

170
00:26:49,585 --> 00:26:52,452
- What's the matter?
- Where we going?

171
00:26:52,555 --> 00:26:54,580
We're gonna fly to I.A.

172
00:26:54,690 --> 00:26:56,920
You're not afraid of flying, are you?

173
00:26:57,026 --> 00:26:59,119
We're... leaving the ground?

174
00:26:59,228 --> 00:27:02,356
- Yeah.
- Why?

175
00:27:02,465 --> 00:27:04,865
Because it's too far to drive.

176
00:27:04,967 --> 00:27:07,231
It would take an extra two days.
I can't afford the time, Trav.

177
00:27:07,336 --> 00:27:09,497
- Why?
- Be --

178
00:27:09,605 --> 00:27:11,630
Look, it's just easier to fly, Trav.

179
00:27:11,741 --> 00:27:14,676
It's faster. Come on.

180
00:27:33,362 --> 00:27:35,330
<i>Let's get you home, okay?</i>

181
00:27:35,431 --> 00:27:38,195
<i>I’m gonna get you home, get you settled,</i>
<i>and then you can do whatever you want.</i>

182
00:27:38,300 --> 00:27:39,858
<i>Let me out, or I'll jump.</i>

183
00:27:39,969 --> 00:27:43,166
<i>Sir, we can't stop the plane</i>
<i>every time somebody gets terrified.</i>

184
00:27:43,272 --> 00:27:46,537
<i>You don't get on a plane</i>
<i>and then refuse to leave the ground.</i>

185
00:27:46,642 --> 00:27:49,941
<i>You don't do things like that.</i>
<i>This isn't the wilderness.</i>

186
00:27:50,046 --> 00:27:52,139
<i>You're living with people now. Okay?</i>

187
00:27:52,248 --> 00:27:53,738
<i>You should've hired a private plane.</i>

188
00:27:53,849 --> 00:27:55,942
Do you realize how many people
you're detaining?

189
00:27:56,052 --> 00:27:57,952
I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

190
00:27:58,054 --> 00:27:59,988
I'm sorry. I'm sorry. Okay?

191
00:28:00,089 --> 00:28:02,922
- Okay, I'm fine now.
- Bye now.

192
00:28:03,025 --> 00:28:05,687
This is getting a little ridiculous, Travis.

193
00:28:07,163 --> 00:28:09,597
Are you gonna leave me?

194
00:28:09,699 --> 00:28:11,667
No, I'm not gonna leave you.

195
00:28:12,902 --> 00:28:15,166
It's all right if you leave me.

196
00:28:15,271 --> 00:28:17,262
I don't know, honey, no.

197
00:28:17,373 --> 00:28:19,603
He just -- He just panicked or something.

198
00:28:21,143 --> 00:28:23,373
Well, it won't do any good
to try another plane.

199
00:28:23,479 --> 00:28:26,937
<i>It wasn't the plane.</i>
<i>He'll just get off again.</i>

200
00:28:27,049 --> 00:28:29,483
Well, we're just gonna
have to drive it. That's all.

201
00:28:29,585 --> 00:28:33,419
<i>Message for Joy Stockwell. Joy Stockwell.</i>
- Yeah, it'll take a good two days.

202
00:28:33,522 --> 00:28:35,888
<i>Austin will arrive at any minute.</i>

203
00:28:35,991 --> 00:28:39,483
<i>I don't understand why you have to have</i>
<i>the very same car you had before.</i>

204
00:28:39,595 --> 00:28:41,222
They're all alike.

205
00:28:41,330 --> 00:28:45,562
All the cars we have here are 'birds,
Olds, Chevies or whatever.

206
00:28:45,668 --> 00:28:47,659
I'm not even sure I can locate
the same car you had before.

207
00:28:47,770 --> 00:28:51,206
I know, I know. Uh, my brother
left something in the car.

208
00:28:51,307 --> 00:28:53,298
We're hoping we can search the car
and find it.

209
00:28:53,409 --> 00:28:56,810
Oh, well, I'll just contact our lost and found
department for you if that's the case.

210
00:28:56,912 --> 00:28:59,608
No, no. We have to have the very same car.

211
00:28:59,715 --> 00:29:02,343
Well, I can't do that.
There's no way I can trace that car for you.

212
00:29:02,451 --> 00:29:05,978
<i>- Why not? You got the license number</i>
<i>right on your form there.</i>
<i>- Well, yes, but--</i>

213
00:29:06,088 --> 00:29:07,988
Just give us the license number.
<i>We'll</i> find it.

214
00:29:08,090 --> 00:29:11,457
But I can't allow you on the lot, sir.

215
00:29:11,560 --> 00:29:13,187
Why not? We're already on it.

216
00:29:13,295 --> 00:29:15,763
I just have to ask you
to come back to the office with me.

217
00:29:18,000 --> 00:29:20,161
Travis!

218
00:29:20,269 --> 00:29:22,066
What?

219
00:29:22,171 --> 00:29:24,662
I don't think we're gonna get
the very same car.

220
00:29:24,774 --> 00:29:28,266
<i>But I can rent you a model</i>
<i>that's just like the one you had before, sir.</i>

221
00:29:29,445 --> 00:29:32,608
We need the same car, Walt.
How are we gonna go in another car?

222
00:29:34,416 --> 00:29:36,316
Give us the number,
will you, please?

223
00:29:37,386 --> 00:29:39,354
Come on. Pretty please.

224
00:29:40,923 --> 00:29:44,359
All right. That number is 667 DJ P.

225
00:29:44,460 --> 00:29:45,290
Six - Remember that?

226
00:29:45,394 --> 00:29:47,362
- 667 DJ P.
- That's right.

227
00:29:47,463 --> 00:29:49,954
- It's -- It's got a bump on the hood.
- Yes, it does.

228
00:30:05,447 --> 00:30:08,211
- What's that?
- What?

229
00:30:08,317 --> 00:30:10,842
That --what you got in your hand.

230
00:30:10,953 --> 00:30:13,683
- A picture.
- Oh? Picture of what?

231
00:30:14,723 --> 00:30:17,021
A picture...

232
00:30:17,126 --> 00:30:20,721
of, uh, Paris.

233
00:30:20,830 --> 00:30:22,627
Paris? Really?

234
00:30:22,731 --> 00:30:25,165
Yes. Picture of a piece of Paris.

235
00:30:25,267 --> 00:30:27,633
Where'd you get a picture of Paris?

236
00:30:27,736 --> 00:30:29,704
- Can I see it?
- Yes.

237
00:30:31,207 --> 00:30:33,937
This is it? This is Paris?

238
00:30:34,043 --> 00:30:36,273
Looks just like Texas to me.

239
00:30:36,378 --> 00:30:38,175
It is.

240
00:30:38,280 --> 00:30:41,010
Paris, Texas?

241
00:30:41,116 --> 00:30:43,584
- It's right here on the map.
- There's really a place called Paris, Texas?

242
00:30:43,686 --> 00:30:45,654
It's right here.

243
00:30:47,957 --> 00:30:50,926
Well, how come you got a picture
of a vacant lot in Paris, Texas?

244
00:30:51,961 --> 00:30:53,861
It's mine.

245
00:30:53,963 --> 00:30:56,955
I know that, but how come you got it?

246
00:30:57,066 --> 00:31:01,162
Uh, I purchased it in-in the mail...

247
00:31:01,270 --> 00:31:03,295
a long time ago.

248
00:31:03,405 --> 00:31:05,669
You bought a picture of a vacant lot
in the mail?

249
00:31:05,774 --> 00:31:08,504
No. I bought the land.

250
00:31:09,578 --> 00:31:11,205
- Oh, you bought that lot.
- Yes.

251
00:31:11,313 --> 00:31:13,281
Oh. Let me see it again.

252
00:31:15,217 --> 00:31:16,616
There's nothin' on it.

253
00:31:16,719 --> 00:31:19,051
Empty.

254
00:31:20,356 --> 00:31:23,723
Why in hell would you want to buy
a vacant lot in Paris, Texas, for Chrissake?

255
00:31:26,295 --> 00:31:28,195
Um...

256
00:31:34,670 --> 00:31:36,570
I forgot.

257
00:31:38,274 --> 00:31:40,936
Here, Trav.

258
00:31:46,949 --> 00:31:50,544
Do you remember
what Mama's very first name was?

259
00:31:50,653 --> 00:31:53,554
- Mary.
- No, I know.

260
00:31:53,656 --> 00:31:57,251
I mean, uh, her--
before she found Daddy.

261
00:31:57,359 --> 00:31:59,953
- Her maiden name?
- Yeah.

262
00:32:00,062 --> 00:32:02,496
You don't remember her maiden name?

263
00:32:02,598 --> 00:32:04,657
No.

264
00:32:04,767 --> 00:32:07,327
Zaquine.

265
00:32:07,436 --> 00:32:10,405
Zaquine. Yeah, Spanish.

266
00:32:10,506 --> 00:32:13,304
- Her father was.
- Yeah?

267
00:32:19,748 --> 00:32:21,716
I don't believe it.

268
00:32:23,252 --> 00:32:25,243
You finally decided to eat.

269
00:32:26,288 --> 00:32:28,415
Eating and talking.

270
00:32:28,524 --> 00:32:31,322
Before you know it, you'll be back
in the land of the living, Trav.

271
00:32:35,731 --> 00:32:37,756
You want me to drive?

272
00:32:37,866 --> 00:32:40,699
Sure. You think you remember how?

273
00:32:40,803 --> 00:32:42,771
My body remembers.

274
00:32:47,743 --> 00:32:50,678
You can sleep while I drive.

275
00:32:50,779 --> 00:32:52,576
Okay.

276
00:33:06,695 --> 00:33:09,220
Well, Trav...

277
00:33:09,331 --> 00:33:11,822
think maybe you're ready to...

278
00:33:11,934 --> 00:33:14,425
tell me what the hell happened to you
over the last four years?

279
00:33:16,772 --> 00:33:18,740
No, not yet.

280
00:33:54,176 --> 00:33:55,473
Travis?

281
00:33:55,577 --> 00:33:57,545
What?

282
00:34:11,460 --> 00:34:16,989
Where are we, Travis? What happened?

283
00:34:17,099 --> 00:34:19,567
Why'd we get off the highway?

284
00:34:19,668 --> 00:34:21,602
Jesus Christ.

285
00:34:21,703 --> 00:34:24,365
I can't even sleep for five minutes
without some crisis.

286
00:34:24,473 --> 00:34:26,441
Why'd you turn off?

287
00:34:29,511 --> 00:34:32,480
I don't know where I turned off.
Didn't have a name.

288
00:34:35,017 --> 00:34:38,418
That's great. That's just dandy.

289
00:34:38,520 --> 00:34:42,217
Here we are in the middle of the Mojave Desert
in a place that doesn't have a name.

290
00:34:44,560 --> 00:34:46,528
I can find the highway again.

291
00:35:07,950 --> 00:35:11,010
Trav, I need to talk to you
a little bit about Hunter.

292
00:35:11,120 --> 00:35:13,088
How old is he now?

293
00:35:13,188 --> 00:35:16,646
He's eight in January.

294
00:35:16,758 --> 00:35:18,749
- He's seven then.
- Yeah.

295
00:35:19,928 --> 00:35:23,762
See, what I wanna talk about is, uh --

296
00:35:23,866 --> 00:35:28,997
Well, he's -- he's like part of the family now.

297
00:35:30,906 --> 00:35:33,340
Anne and me are like his parents now.

298
00:35:34,510 --> 00:35:37,775
- Anne's your wife.
- Yeah. You remember her, don't you?

299
00:35:37,880 --> 00:35:40,849
No. Does he think that you're his father?

300
00:35:42,784 --> 00:35:46,720
Well --Anne told him you were coming.

301
00:35:48,490 --> 00:35:50,253
Well, who does he think I am?

302
00:35:50,359 --> 00:35:54,523
I -- I told him you're his father.

303
00:35:55,631 --> 00:35:57,963
But, see --

304
00:35:58,066 --> 00:36:00,591
Well, you've been gone a long time, Trav.

305
00:36:00,702 --> 00:36:03,398
How long have I been gone?
Do you know?

306
00:36:04,940 --> 00:36:07,170
Four years.

307
00:36:07,276 --> 00:36:09,870
Is four years a long time?

308
00:36:11,780 --> 00:36:14,271
Well, it is for a little boy.

309
00:36:16,218 --> 00:36:17,913
It's half his life.

310
00:36:19,955 --> 00:36:21,855
Half a boy's life.

311
00:36:25,594 --> 00:36:28,757
- I remember now.
<i>- What?</i>

312
00:36:32,201 --> 00:36:35,466
- Why I bought that land.
<i>- Oh. Why?</i>

313
00:36:35,571 --> 00:36:39,302
Well, Mama once told me that, uh...

314
00:36:39,408 --> 00:36:43,174
that's where she and Daddy
first, uh, made love.

315
00:36:44,479 --> 00:36:48,210
<i>- Oh. ln Paris, Texas?</i>
- Yeah.

316
00:36:48,317 --> 00:36:50,308
<i>- She told you that?</i>
- Yeah.

317
00:36:52,487 --> 00:36:54,387
So...

318
00:36:55,757 --> 00:36:59,056
I figured that that's where I -- I began.

319
00:36:59,161 --> 00:37:02,927
<i>I-I mean me, Travis Clay Henderson.</i>

320
00:37:03,031 --> 00:37:05,829
<i>They named me that.</i>

321
00:37:05,934 --> 00:37:07,834
<i>I started out there.</i>

322
00:37:09,504 --> 00:37:12,234
<i>- Paris, Texas, huh?</i>
<i>- Yeah.</i>

323
00:37:16,311 --> 00:37:18,541
So, you think maybe
you were conceived there?

324
00:37:20,215 --> 00:37:23,446
<i>- Yeah.</i>
- Well, you could be right, Travis.

325
00:37:25,287 --> 00:37:27,517
Daddy always had a joke about it.

326
00:37:28,557 --> 00:37:31,185
<i>What was the joke?</i>

327
00:37:31,293 --> 00:37:35,855
He, uh -- He would introduce Mama
as the girl he met in Paris.

328
00:37:36,898 --> 00:37:41,335
And then he'd wait, uh,
before he said "Texas"...

329
00:37:41,436 --> 00:37:46,100
till everybody thought that... he meant --

330
00:37:46,208 --> 00:37:49,507
He would wait before he said "Texas"
till everybody thought --

331
00:37:49,611 --> 00:37:53,103
after everybody thought he was
talking about Paris, France.

332
00:37:53,215 --> 00:37:55,513
He-He always laughed real hard about it.

333
00:37:58,820 --> 00:38:01,618
<i>So you live in</i> Los Angeles, <i>huh?</i>

334
00:38:01,723 --> 00:38:06,251
Well, we live in the suburbs,
but I got my business in town.

335
00:38:06,361 --> 00:38:08,352
<i>Yeah? What's your business?</i>

336
00:38:08,463 --> 00:38:10,795
I make billboard signs for advertising.

337
00:38:11,933 --> 00:38:15,664
<i>Oh, yeah. So</i> you're <i>the one</i>
<i>who makes those, huh?</i>

338
00:38:15,771 --> 00:38:18,604
<i>I love those.</i>
<i>Some of them are beautiful.</i>

339
00:38:18,707 --> 00:38:21,437
I'm not the only one in the world
that makes 'em, Trav.

340
00:38:45,267 --> 00:38:47,735
Trav? This way.

341
00:38:47,836 --> 00:38:50,862
Nice, huh? Just been in here three months.

342
00:38:50,972 --> 00:38:54,601
I really like it, but I took a beating
on the financing, I tell ya.

343
00:38:54,710 --> 00:38:57,941
Like everybody else nowadays, I guess.

344
00:39:03,885 --> 00:39:07,651
Hi, baby.
Mmm, everything okay here?

345
00:39:07,756 --> 00:39:10,247
Oh, sure. We just missed you a lot.

346
00:39:10,359 --> 00:39:13,351
Yeah. I missed you too.

347
00:39:13,462 --> 00:39:15,487
- Come on in.
- Travis.

348
00:39:20,602 --> 00:39:22,536
My God.

349
00:39:22,637 --> 00:39:26,334
We were beginning to wonder
if we'd ever see you again.

350
00:39:26,441 --> 00:39:29,001
It's been so long.

351
00:39:29,111 --> 00:39:31,545
Did you have a good trip?

352
00:39:31,646 --> 00:39:33,614
Yeah, it was fine.

353
00:39:36,718 --> 00:39:38,618
Hunter?

354
00:39:49,531 --> 00:39:53,763
Hunter, this is Travis.

355
00:40:07,616 --> 00:40:09,516
Hi.

356
00:40:11,787 --> 00:40:13,982
Hi.

357
00:40:22,564 --> 00:40:26,000
I bet it was really hot coming across
the Mojave Desert.

358
00:40:28,437 --> 00:40:30,667
Yes.

359
00:40:30,772 --> 00:40:32,967
Too bad you had to drive.

360
00:40:33,074 --> 00:40:35,565
<i>What happened?</i>

361
00:40:35,677 --> 00:40:39,135
<i>Well, Travis just, uh, didn't feel like flying.</i>

362
00:40:39,247 --> 00:40:41,044
Oh, I don't blame you.

363
00:40:41,149 --> 00:40:46,177
I can't stand airplanes anymore,
especially since we live in this house.

364
00:40:46,288 --> 00:40:49,655
<i>All we hear is planes</i>
<i>day in and day out.</i>

365
00:40:49,758 --> 00:40:52,158
I like 'em.

366
00:40:59,067 --> 00:41:01,399
You used to fly, didn't you, Travis?

367
00:41:03,538 --> 00:41:05,768
No.

368
00:41:06,908 --> 00:41:11,538
Oh. I thought I remembered Jane
telling me once...

369
00:41:11,646 --> 00:41:16,674
<i>that you flew to Dallas together...</i>
<i>or somewhere.</i>

370
00:41:16,785 --> 00:41:19,083
Um --

371
00:41:19,187 --> 00:41:21,087
Maybe I'm mistaken.

372
00:41:41,710 --> 00:41:46,841
<i>Honey, he hasn't slept in a bed</i>
<i>since we started for here. I swear to God.</i>

373
00:41:46,948 --> 00:41:49,280
I don't think that's even necessary.

374
00:41:49,384 --> 00:41:51,682
Where has he been sleeping then?

375
00:41:51,786 --> 00:41:54,687
Well, he doesn't sleep.

376
00:41:54,789 --> 00:41:57,053
He has to sleep somewhere.

377
00:41:57,158 --> 00:42:01,254
Okay, but I don't think
he's even gonna use it.

378
00:42:01,363 --> 00:42:03,388
He's got to get tired sometime.

379
00:42:07,469 --> 00:42:10,438
Oh. There is a towel for you, Travis.

380
00:42:10,539 --> 00:42:13,702
And some underwear
and socks from Walt.

381
00:42:13,808 --> 00:42:15,969
- Oh.
- Good night.

382
00:42:16,077 --> 00:42:18,568
Good night.

383
00:42:18,680 --> 00:42:20,648
Thank you.

384
00:42:22,017 --> 00:42:25,145
Okay.

385
00:42:25,253 --> 00:42:27,813
Get some shut-eye.

386
00:42:27,923 --> 00:42:30,187
Okay.

387
00:42:30,292 --> 00:42:32,192
- Sweet dreams.
- All right.

388
00:43:41,429 --> 00:43:43,397
You polished them.

389
00:43:45,567 --> 00:43:48,331
That's very nice of you, Travis.

390
00:43:49,471 --> 00:43:51,939
Would you like to come in
and have some breakfast?

391
00:43:54,275 --> 00:43:56,175
Aren't you hungry?

392
00:43:57,212 --> 00:44:00,340
We are going to have strawberry waffles.

393
00:44:00,448 --> 00:44:02,814
Do you like them?

394
00:44:02,917 --> 00:44:04,817
Do you want some?

395
00:44:13,862 --> 00:44:17,730
<i>Well, there is hot coffee on the stove</i>
<i>if you want some.</i>

396
00:44:20,735 --> 00:44:22,703
Look at that truck.

397
00:45:00,875 --> 00:45:02,467
Hi.

398
00:45:37,846 --> 00:45:40,713
- Decided to rough it, huh?
- Yeah.

399
00:45:42,083 --> 00:45:43,983
What'd you do -- spit-shine these?

400
00:45:44,085 --> 00:45:45,985
I can get you a job at the airport
doing that.

401
00:45:47,722 --> 00:45:52,216
Hey. You wanna trade these new boots
for those old boots?

402
00:45:52,327 --> 00:45:54,454
Yeah, you can wear 'em.

403
00:45:56,831 --> 00:45:58,731
Thank you.

404
00:46:24,759 --> 00:46:26,693
<i>Travis?</i>

405
00:46:26,795 --> 00:46:30,390
<i>I have to rush off</i>
<i>to get Hunter to school on time.</i>

406
00:46:30,498 --> 00:46:32,489
We will be back this afternoon.

407
00:46:32,600 --> 00:46:35,535
Walt's office number
is on the dining room table.

408
00:46:35,637 --> 00:46:37,605
See you later.

409
00:46:37,705 --> 00:46:39,502
- Okay.
<i>- Bye.</i>

410
00:47:13,975 --> 00:47:15,875
- Anne?
<i>- Yeah?</i>

411
00:47:15,977 --> 00:47:19,310
I was just thinking. Maybe, uh, I can
meet Hunter after school...

412
00:47:19,414 --> 00:47:21,746
and we could walk home together
if he wants to.

413
00:47:21,850 --> 00:47:24,717
Oh, that sounds like a great idea, Travis.

414
00:47:26,287 --> 00:47:29,723
<i>Walk home?</i>
<i>I don't wanna walk home, Mom.</i>

415
00:47:31,059 --> 00:47:34,153
- Why?
- Nobody walks. Everybody drives.

416
00:47:34,262 --> 00:47:36,389
- Come on, Hunter.
- No.

417
00:47:36,497 --> 00:47:38,294
It won't hurt you to walk home
once in your life.

418
00:47:38,399 --> 00:47:42,096
- No, no. I don't want to.
<i>- I don't wanna walk, Mom. Everybody else--</i>

419
00:47:42,203 --> 00:47:44,296
- Travis, I insist. He'll wait for you out in front.
- Everybody will see me.

420
00:47:44,405 --> 00:47:47,602
<i>Walt can tell you how to get there.</i>
<i>It's not far.</i>

421
00:47:47,709 --> 00:47:50,109
And get in the car, Hunter.
We are late as it is.

422
00:47:54,983 --> 00:47:56,883
<i>You're mean.</i>

423
00:48:43,264 --> 00:48:45,630
Awesome!

424
00:48:51,773 --> 00:48:53,673
<i>I flunked kindergarten.</i>

425
00:48:59,047 --> 00:49:01,447
- Can I come with you?
- Sure.

426
00:49:39,821 --> 00:49:42,187
<i>I’m really sorry about this, Travis.</i>

427
00:49:43,725 --> 00:49:46,694
It's not easy for him, Anne.

428
00:49:52,934 --> 00:49:54,993
Anne, it's okay. He's in here.

429
00:50:03,044 --> 00:50:04,944
What are you doin'?

430
00:50:05,046 --> 00:50:07,241
Driving.

431
00:50:07,348 --> 00:50:11,307
- Where to?
-Just driving.

432
00:50:11,419 --> 00:50:14,047
You're not hiding out in there, are you?

433
00:50:14,155 --> 00:50:16,123
No.

434
00:50:20,995 --> 00:50:24,931
Hunter, Travis is your real dad.
You know that, don't you?

435
00:50:27,201 --> 00:50:31,035
Dad, when are they gonna make spaceships
like they make cars?

436
00:50:33,908 --> 00:50:36,741
Hunter, I'm asking you a question.
Can you answer it?

437
00:50:36,844 --> 00:50:38,937
What?

438
00:50:42,050 --> 00:50:47,420
Well, Travis went to meet you at school,
and he wanted to walk you home.

439
00:50:47,522 --> 00:50:50,355
Nobody walks.

440
00:50:50,458 --> 00:50:52,619
That's not the point.

441
00:50:52,727 --> 00:50:57,824
<i>Travis is your real dad,</i>
<i>and he wants to talk to you.</i>

442
00:51:00,802 --> 00:51:02,997
Why? What about?

443
00:51:04,972 --> 00:51:08,271
Okay, come on.
Let's go have dinner. Come on.

444
00:51:18,019 --> 00:51:20,010
Hey, Trav, do you remember the time...

445
00:51:20,121 --> 00:51:23,181
that Anne and me came down to visit you
about five years ago?

446
00:51:24,892 --> 00:51:27,326
No.

447
00:51:27,428 --> 00:51:30,522
You and Jane were down in Texas,
right there on the coast.

448
00:51:30,631 --> 00:51:35,193
<i>Hunter was about three.</i>
<i>Don't you remember that?</i>

449
00:51:38,806 --> 00:51:42,298
- No.
- I remember. We went fishing.

450
00:51:43,244 --> 00:51:48,147
<i>Yeah. I took some Super 8 on that trip.</i>
<i>And I put it all together.</i>

451
00:51:48,249 --> 00:51:49,910
I thought maybe you might like
to see some of it.

452
00:51:50,017 --> 00:51:52,144
Wh-What is it?

453
00:51:52,253 --> 00:51:54,380
Movies. You know, Super 8.

454
00:51:54,489 --> 00:51:56,047
Oh.

455
00:51:56,157 --> 00:51:59,490
<i>Walt, maybe Travis doesn't want--</i>

456
00:51:59,594 --> 00:52:02,222
What?

457
00:52:03,097 --> 00:52:06,999
Well, maybe he'd like to wait a while
before he looks at it.

458
00:52:07,101 --> 00:52:10,502
Well, it's up to him.

459
00:52:10,605 --> 00:52:12,630
I just thought maybe
you'd like to see some of it.

460
00:52:12,740 --> 00:52:15,038
Movies? Sure.

461
00:52:15,143 --> 00:52:17,236
<i>Great. There's some great stuff in it.</i>

462
00:52:17,345 --> 00:52:19,370
Some great shots of Hunter in it.

463
00:52:19,480 --> 00:52:21,505
I've already seen it.

464
00:52:21,616 --> 00:52:24,608
Well, you have to see it again.

465
00:52:24,719 --> 00:52:27,586
- Come on. Help me set up the projector.
- Okay.

466
00:53:55,209 --> 00:53:59,373
- That's me driving.
- I know. You're gonna be good.

467
00:57:04,064 --> 00:57:06,055
Time for bed now, Hunter.

468
00:57:06,167 --> 00:57:09,261
Aw, Mom.

469
00:57:09,370 --> 00:57:11,338
Don't complain. It's past 10.00.

470
00:57:13,874 --> 00:57:15,774
- Good night, Dad.
- Good night, baby.

471
00:57:15,876 --> 00:57:17,571
Mmm.

472
00:57:22,049 --> 00:57:24,017
Good night, Dad.

473
00:57:29,356 --> 00:57:32,325
Do you think he still loves her?

474
00:57:32,426 --> 00:57:35,361
How would I know that, Hunter?

475
00:57:35,463 --> 00:57:37,431
I think he does.

476
00:57:38,866 --> 00:57:42,563
- How can you tell?
- Well, the way he looked at her.

477
00:57:42,670 --> 00:57:45,036
You mean when he saw her
in the movie?

478
00:57:45,139 --> 00:57:48,199
Yeah, but that's not her.

479
00:57:48,309 --> 00:57:50,777
What do you mean?

480
00:57:50,878 --> 00:57:52,846
That's only her in a movie...

481
00:57:54,381 --> 00:57:57,077
a long time ago...

482
00:57:57,184 --> 00:58:00,950
in a galaxy far, far away.

483
00:58:37,391 --> 00:58:41,191
- What are you looking for?
- Uh, I'm looking for...

484
00:58:41,295 --> 00:58:43,729
uh, <i>the</i> father.

485
00:58:43,831 --> 00:58:48,530
- Your father?
- No, no. Just a father. Any father.

486
00:58:48,636 --> 00:58:50,627
What does a father look like?

487
00:58:50,738 --> 00:58:53,730
There are many different kinds
of fathers, señor Travis.

488
00:58:53,841 --> 00:58:55,900
Well, I just -- I just need one.

489
00:58:56,010 --> 00:58:59,810
- You think you're gonna find him in there?
- Well, I don't know where else to look.

490
00:58:59,914 --> 00:59:03,315
Oh, I see. You want to look like a father.

491
00:59:03,417 --> 00:59:05,112
- Yeah.
- Mmm.

492
00:59:05,219 --> 00:59:07,119
<i>Ahora.</i> Tell me.

493
00:59:07,221 --> 00:59:10,122
Do you want to be a rich father?

494
00:59:10,224 --> 00:59:12,522
Uh, no.

495
00:59:12,626 --> 00:59:14,719
- A poor one?
- No.

496
00:59:14,828 --> 00:59:16,819
<i>Rues, ¿cómo pues?</i>

497
00:59:16,931 --> 00:59:20,890
- Uh, in between.
- No, no. There is no in between, huh?

498
00:59:21,001 --> 00:59:23,333
You either have to be a rich father
or a poor one.

499
00:59:23,437 --> 00:59:25,337
- Rich.
- <i>Bueno.</i>

500
00:59:25,439 --> 00:59:27,407
<i>Un momento. A ver.</i>

501
00:59:28,576 --> 00:59:30,737
<i>Ahora, sí.</i> Okay.

502
00:59:31,779 --> 00:59:33,770
<i>A ver.</i> Huh?

503
00:59:38,218 --> 00:59:40,277
<i>-¿Qué tal? ¿Eh?</i>
<i>- Está bueno.</i>

504
00:59:40,387 --> 00:59:42,855
Okay. One thing you must remember.

505
00:59:42,957 --> 00:59:45,255
To be a rich father, señor Travis...

506
00:59:45,359 --> 00:59:48,328
you must look to the sky
and never at the ground, eh?

507
00:59:48,429 --> 00:59:50,420
<i>Mire.</i>

508
00:59:50,531 --> 00:59:52,089
Little higher.

509
00:59:52,199 --> 00:59:54,133
<i>Eso.</i> Mm-hmm.

510
00:59:54,234 --> 00:59:56,225
<i>Ahora. Camine.</i>

511
01:00:00,207 --> 01:00:03,074
<i>No. Este--</i>

512
01:00:03,177 --> 01:00:05,145
You must walk stiff, señor Travis.

513
01:00:09,216 --> 01:00:11,480
<i>Con confianza. ¿Me entiende?</i>

514
01:00:11,585 --> 01:00:13,712
<i>Um, con respeto.</i>

515
01:00:13,821 --> 01:00:15,948
- Uh, dignity.
<i>- Eso.</i>

516
01:00:16,056 --> 01:00:18,490
<i>Con dignidad.</i>

517
01:00:18,592 --> 01:00:20,492
<i>Ahora.</i>

518
01:00:28,202 --> 01:00:30,170
Mm-hmm.

519
01:00:32,573 --> 01:00:34,564
You got it.

520
01:00:54,428 --> 01:00:56,396
Who is that guy?
You know him?

521
01:00:57,431 --> 01:00:59,695
Yeah. He's my father's brother.

522
01:01:02,302 --> 01:01:06,068
No. They're both brothers.

523
01:01:06,173 --> 01:01:09,540
No. they're both --
They're both fathers.

524
01:01:11,912 --> 01:01:13,903
No. Aw, forget it.

525
01:01:14,014 --> 01:01:16,983
- But both whose father?
- My father.

526
01:01:17,084 --> 01:01:19,416
How-How can you have two fathers?

527
01:01:19,520 --> 01:01:22,512
Just lucky, I guess.

528
01:01:22,623 --> 01:01:25,114
- Well, bye.
- Bye.

529
01:03:17,037 --> 01:03:18,937
<i>That's my dad's suit.</i>

530
01:03:20,207 --> 01:03:21,640
I mean Walt.

531
01:03:21,742 --> 01:03:23,710
That's okay if you call him "Dad."

532
01:03:24,878 --> 01:03:27,847
Yeah, I borrowed it from him.
He said it was okay.

533
01:03:33,287 --> 01:03:35,187
What are those pictures?

534
01:03:35,289 --> 01:03:37,189
That's my dad --

535
01:03:38,325 --> 01:03:40,555
and your grandfather.

536
01:03:44,164 --> 01:03:47,258
- What was his name?
- Travis.

537
01:03:47,367 --> 01:03:50,495
- Same as yours.
- Mm-hmm.

538
01:03:50,604 --> 01:03:52,504
Where is he now?

539
01:03:53,740 --> 01:03:57,904
He died... couple of years after this picture.

540
01:03:58,011 --> 01:03:59,911
In that car.

541
01:04:00,013 --> 01:04:02,174
- Oh. He's dead.
- Mm-hmm.

542
01:04:03,383 --> 01:04:06,284
But can you feel that he's dead?

543
01:04:06,386 --> 01:04:08,081
What do you mean?

544
01:04:08,188 --> 01:04:11,783
You know when he was walking around
and talking, right?

545
01:04:11,892 --> 01:04:15,157
- Yeah.
- So can you feel that he's gone?

546
01:04:17,064 --> 01:04:18,691
Yeah, sometimes.

547
01:04:18,799 --> 01:04:20,767
I know he's dead.

548
01:04:21,935 --> 01:04:24,369
I never felt like you were dead.

549
01:04:24,471 --> 01:04:28,703
I could always feel you walking around
and talking someplace.

550
01:04:28,809 --> 01:04:32,040
- Yeah?
- I feel Mom too.

551
01:04:32,145 --> 01:04:34,136
- You do?
- Don't you?

552
01:04:35,582 --> 01:04:37,482
Yeah.

553
01:04:40,254 --> 01:04:42,313
That's me when I was in the navy.

554
01:04:42,422 --> 01:04:44,515
<i>Hmm. You were a general?</i>

555
01:04:44,625 --> 01:04:46,991
No. That's when I was --

556
01:04:47,094 --> 01:04:48,527
That's when I was in the band.

557
01:04:48,629 --> 01:04:51,257
- Oh.
- The high school band.

558
01:04:52,733 --> 01:04:54,462
Now, here's you.
I like this picture.

559
01:04:54,568 --> 01:04:58,470
That -- Look at that.
That is really wild.

560
01:04:58,572 --> 01:05:01,769
<i>It’s weird when it-- when it--</i>
<i>when there's water in between.</i>

561
01:05:01,875 --> 01:05:04,935
And then it turns into nothing.
Then it goes -- pshh.

562
01:05:05,045 --> 01:05:07,513
Yeah. That's a great picture.

563
01:05:07,614 --> 01:05:10,048
And this is my mom.

564
01:05:11,785 --> 01:05:13,753
Your grandmother.

565
01:05:18,525 --> 01:05:20,425
I don't know.

566
01:05:23,797 --> 01:05:27,824
It just seems like everything
has changed between us so fast --

567
01:05:27,935 --> 01:05:30,426
ever since Travis came.

568
01:05:30,537 --> 01:05:32,232
What's changed?

569
01:05:34,074 --> 01:05:35,974
I'm just afraid.

570
01:05:37,511 --> 01:05:41,003
- Afraid of Travis?
- No.

571
01:05:41,114 --> 01:05:43,014
Then what?

572
01:05:45,118 --> 01:05:48,315
Of what will happen to us
if we lose Hunter.

573
01:05:50,657 --> 01:05:53,490
We're not gonna lose Hunter.

574
01:05:53,593 --> 01:05:56,824
Then why do you keep
pushing them together?

575
01:05:56,930 --> 01:05:59,990
It's almost as if you wanted him to leave.

576
01:06:00,100 --> 01:06:03,695
<i>- Who?</i>
- Hunter.

577
01:06:03,804 --> 01:06:06,272
You know what I'm talking about.

578
01:06:06,373 --> 01:06:09,900
You keep promoting
this father-son business between them.

579
01:06:10,010 --> 01:06:12,137
It's not "business."

580
01:06:12,245 --> 01:06:16,045
Travis is his father,
and Hunter is his son.

581
01:06:16,149 --> 01:06:20,176
<i>That's a fact. We've known that all along.</i>

582
01:06:21,388 --> 01:06:24,824
<i>- Travis happens to be my brother.</i>
<i>-I know he is.</i>

583
01:06:24,925 --> 01:06:27,655
<i>Well, what's this promotion bullshit?</i>

584
01:06:27,761 --> 01:06:32,528
<i>You want us to go on pretending</i>
<i>that we're the parents of my brother's son?</i>

585
01:06:32,632 --> 01:06:34,793
<i>How long do you expect Hunter to buy that?</i>

586
01:06:34,901 --> 01:06:37,301
<i>I was never pretending.</i>

587
01:06:37,404 --> 01:06:41,238
<i>I love him, just like he was</i>
<i>my own flesh and blood.</i>

588
01:06:42,609 --> 01:06:44,577
<i>So do I.</i>

589
01:06:54,821 --> 01:06:58,120
- Hi, Anne.
- Hi, Travis.

590
01:06:58,225 --> 01:07:00,989
You don't sleep much, do you?

591
01:07:10,037 --> 01:07:12,631
Travis.

592
01:07:12,739 --> 01:07:14,900
There is something I have to tell you.

593
01:07:15,008 --> 01:07:20,378
I was not going to, because somehow
it makes things easier that nobody knows.

594
01:07:21,715 --> 01:07:24,684
I never even told Walt or Hunter.

595
01:07:26,253 --> 01:07:28,221
Well, what is it?

596
01:07:30,424 --> 01:07:33,621
After Hunter came to live with us...

597
01:07:33,727 --> 01:07:37,788
Jane used to call asking about him.

598
01:07:39,199 --> 01:07:43,533
<i>She made me promise</i>
<i>not to tell anyone she was calling.</i>

599
01:07:43,637 --> 01:07:45,605
<i>Did she ask about me?</i>

600
01:07:48,208 --> 01:07:50,733
Yes, in the beginning.

601
01:07:54,881 --> 01:07:57,645
Where did she call from?

602
01:07:57,751 --> 01:07:59,685
Places in Texas.

603
01:07:59,786 --> 01:08:01,686
What places?

604
01:08:05,058 --> 01:08:06,958
Let me finish, Travis.

605
01:08:09,796 --> 01:08:14,028
After what happened
between you and Jane...

606
01:08:14,134 --> 01:08:16,625
she decided Hunter should be with us.

607
01:08:18,472 --> 01:08:21,134
She said she couldn't be a mother
to him anymore.

608
01:08:29,249 --> 01:08:32,377
She stopped being a mother to him
a long time before that.

609
01:08:45,365 --> 01:08:49,665
Travis, I don't want to feel
I'm hiding something.

610
01:08:56,710 --> 01:08:58,735
She was young.

611
01:09:03,717 --> 01:09:07,084
She wanted something.
I just couldn't figure out what it was.

612
01:09:14,494 --> 01:09:17,725
I just didn't realize
how much rage I had.

613
01:09:26,006 --> 01:09:29,373
A little more than a year ago,
she stopped calling.

614
01:09:29,476 --> 01:09:31,706
I haven't heard from her since then.

615
01:09:32,846 --> 01:09:34,746
Nothing?

616
01:09:36,049 --> 01:09:38,415
Not a word.

617
01:09:38,518 --> 01:09:40,418
But on the last call...

618
01:09:41,555 --> 01:09:44,718
she asked me to open a bank account
for Hunter.

619
01:09:45,992 --> 01:09:47,459
A bank account?

620
01:09:47,561 --> 01:09:50,359
All I know about Jane now is...

621
01:09:51,531 --> 01:09:56,491
she goes to this bank
on the fifth of each month...

622
01:09:56,603 --> 01:09:59,071
and wires money for Hunter.

623
01:10:03,410 --> 01:10:06,174
Jane still sends him money?

624
01:10:06,279 --> 01:10:09,009
Sometimes a hundred dollars.

625
01:10:09,115 --> 01:10:12,278
Sometimes 50 or five.

626
01:10:12,385 --> 01:10:14,910
For Hunter's future.

627
01:10:15,021 --> 01:10:17,216
I had the bank trace the wire.

628
01:10:18,458 --> 01:10:20,426
It comes from a bank in Houston.

629
01:10:20,527 --> 01:10:22,119
What bank?

630
01:10:23,763 --> 01:10:26,994
I wrote it down if you want it.

631
01:10:30,036 --> 01:10:34,097
- What's the date today?
- The first of November.

632
01:10:38,945 --> 01:10:41,675
"I don't think we should do that anymore."
"You're right."

633
01:10:43,950 --> 01:10:47,681
"Heh. I meant the other thing." "Oh."

634
01:11:06,339 --> 01:11:11,208
<i>You will all be caught with your diapers down!</i>

635
01:11:11,311 --> 01:11:13,541
<i>That is a promise!</i>

636
01:11:13,647 --> 01:11:18,175
<i>I make you this promise</i>
<i>on my mother's head!</i>

637
01:11:18,285 --> 01:11:24,053
<i>For right here, today,</i>
<i>standing on the very head of my mother...</i>

638
01:11:24,157 --> 01:11:27,183
<i>which is now on God's green earth...</i>

639
01:11:27,294 --> 01:11:31,025
<i>which everybody who wasn't born</i>
<i>in a fuckin' sewer...</i>

640
01:11:31,131 --> 01:11:35,932
<i>ought to know and understand</i>
<i>to the very marrow of their bones!</i>

641
01:11:37,437 --> 01:11:40,838
<i>They will invade you in your beds!</i>

642
01:11:40,940 --> 01:11:44,671
<i>They will snatch you from your hot tubs!</i>

643
01:11:44,778 --> 01:11:49,613
<i>They will pluck you right out</i>
<i>of your fancy sports cars!</i>

644
01:11:49,716 --> 01:11:51,911
<i>There is nowhere...</i>

645
01:11:53,953 --> 01:11:59,414
<i>absolutely nowhere</i>
<i>in this godforsaken valley--</i>

646
01:11:59,526 --> 01:12:04,463
<i>I’m talking about from the range</i>
<i>of my voice right here...</i>

647
01:12:04,564 --> 01:12:09,934
<i>clear out to the goddamn Mojave Desert</i>
<i>and beyond that--</i>

648
01:12:10,036 --> 01:12:12,630
<i>clear out past Barstow...</i>

649
01:12:13,740 --> 01:12:17,767
<i>and everywhere else in the valley</i>
<i>all the way to Arizona.</i>

650
01:12:17,877 --> 01:12:21,643
None of that area
will be called a safety zone!

651
01:12:21,748 --> 01:12:23,909
There will be no safety zone!

652
01:12:24,017 --> 01:12:27,919
I can guarantee you the safety zone
will be eliminated!

653
01:12:28,021 --> 01:12:30,353
Eradicated!

654
01:12:30,457 --> 01:12:35,724
You will all be extradited
to the land of no return!

655
01:12:35,829 --> 01:12:38,992
It's a navigation to nowhere!

656
01:12:39,099 --> 01:12:42,068
And if you think that's going to be fun...

657
01:12:42,168 --> 01:12:45,137
you've got another thing comin'.

658
01:12:46,406 --> 01:12:48,806
I may be a slime bucket...

659
01:12:48,908 --> 01:12:50,808
but believe me...

660
01:12:50,910 --> 01:12:53,811
<i>I know what the hell I’m talking about!</i>

661
01:12:53,913 --> 01:12:56,040
<i>I’m not crazy!</i>

662
01:12:56,149 --> 01:12:58,982
<i>And don't say I didn't warn you!</i>

663
01:12:59,085 --> 01:13:02,418
<i>I warned you! I warned all of you!</i>

664
01:13:13,533 --> 01:13:15,933
Thought you were afraid of heights.

665
01:13:16,035 --> 01:13:19,266
No, I'm not afraid of heights.
I'm afraid of falling.

666
01:13:19,372 --> 01:13:23,274
- Oh, yeah? Well, just don't look down.
- No.

667
01:13:23,376 --> 01:13:27,938
Uh, too bad things don't look the same
on the ground.

668
01:13:28,047 --> 01:13:29,947
What do you mean?

669
01:13:30,049 --> 01:13:33,450
Well, things are clearer up here.

670
01:13:34,754 --> 01:13:36,654
<i>Might clear things up.</i>

671
01:13:36,756 --> 01:13:39,657
<i>Yeah, I had a talk with Anne last night.</i>

672
01:13:39,759 --> 01:13:41,659
<i>Yeah, she's pretty upset.</i>

673
01:13:41,761 --> 01:13:43,729
Yeah, I know.

674
01:13:45,398 --> 01:13:47,298
I'm gonna leave.

675
01:13:47,400 --> 01:13:49,300
- What?
- I'm leaving.

676
01:13:49,402 --> 01:13:52,303
Hey, I didn't tell you this
in order to make you leave.

677
01:13:52,405 --> 01:13:54,396
- I'm not trying to get rid of you, Travis.
- I know that.

678
01:13:54,507 --> 01:13:58,739
What good is that gonna do?
That's not gonna solve anything.

679
01:13:58,845 --> 01:14:00,813
I'm gonna find Jane.

680
01:14:02,482 --> 01:14:04,177
How are you gonna do that?

681
01:14:04,284 --> 01:14:06,582
It's been four years.
She's completely disappeared.

682
01:14:06,686 --> 01:14:08,950
I tried to find her.
I tried everything. I couldn't find her.

683
01:14:09,055 --> 01:14:11,683
Yeah, well, I haven't tried yet.
I can find her.

684
01:14:11,791 --> 01:14:15,090
- What makes you so sure?
- I just know.

685
01:14:15,195 --> 01:14:18,096
- Can we go down now?
- No!

686
01:14:18,198 --> 01:14:22,259
Goddamn it!
You tell me what happened, Travis!

687
01:14:22,368 --> 01:14:24,734
I'm sick of this fuckin' mystery.

688
01:14:24,838 --> 01:14:28,274
I've been treating you like a spoiled kid
ever since I picked you up in the desert.

689
01:14:28,374 --> 01:14:31,502
Now you tell me
what happened with you and Jane!

690
01:14:32,545 --> 01:14:34,445
Shit!

691
01:14:34,547 --> 01:14:37,107
I know. It's none of my business.

692
01:14:38,318 --> 01:14:41,719
<i>Uh, I’m gonna need to take, uh...</i>

693
01:14:41,821 --> 01:14:44,790
<i>money, credit cards.</i>

694
01:14:44,891 --> 01:14:46,791
<i>All right, sure. You can have 'em.</i>

695
01:14:46,893 --> 01:14:49,726
<i>- You know you'll get it back.</i>
<i>- Forget that. You can have it.</i>

696
01:14:49,829 --> 01:14:52,297
<i>I’m gonna find her, Walt.</i>

697
01:15:17,490 --> 01:15:19,458
Hunter!

698
01:15:28,701 --> 01:15:30,498
Is that your car?

699
01:15:34,040 --> 01:15:37,441
Yep. Come on.

700
01:15:37,544 --> 01:15:39,739
Radical!

701
01:15:53,493 --> 01:15:55,620
This is not bad stuff.

702
01:15:57,196 --> 01:15:59,596
Anne puts it in lunch every day.

703
01:15:59,699 --> 01:16:02,600
<i>La vache qui rit.</i> Sticky.

704
01:16:02,702 --> 01:16:04,670
<i>La vache</i> what?

705
01:16:06,272 --> 01:16:08,240
<i>Rit. Rit.</i>

706
01:16:08,341 --> 01:16:10,468
<i>Rit. Rit.</i>

707
01:16:11,544 --> 01:16:13,512
I like it.

708
01:16:14,981 --> 01:16:17,211
- Dad?
- Yeah?

709
01:16:17,317 --> 01:16:19,785
Where'd you go all that time?

710
01:16:22,422 --> 01:16:24,322
Mexico.

711
01:16:24,424 --> 01:16:26,392
How come?

712
01:16:27,660 --> 01:16:30,322
I didn't know where else to go.

713
01:16:30,430 --> 01:16:33,126
Where did Mom go?

714
01:16:34,233 --> 01:16:36,133
I don't know.

715
01:16:36,235 --> 01:16:38,635
But right now, she's somewhere in Houston.

716
01:16:38,738 --> 01:16:41,002
That's where the space center is.

717
01:16:41,107 --> 01:16:43,075
Yeah.

718
01:16:44,777 --> 01:16:47,678
That's what I wanted to talk to you about.

719
01:16:47,780 --> 01:16:50,681
- I gotta go away now.
- Why?

720
01:16:50,783 --> 01:16:53,081
Because I'm gonna find her.

721
01:16:53,186 --> 01:16:55,347
What about me? You just found me.

722
01:16:55,455 --> 01:16:57,355
Can I come with?

723
01:17:01,094 --> 01:17:02,994
What about Walt and Anne?

724
01:17:03,096 --> 01:17:06,327
You mean we'd never come back here?

725
01:17:06,432 --> 01:17:08,491
Well, sure, but...

726
01:17:08,601 --> 01:17:10,933
I don't know when.

727
01:17:19,545 --> 01:17:21,513
I want to come with.

728
01:17:24,517 --> 01:17:27,953
I wanna find her too.
When do we go?

729
01:17:32,458 --> 01:17:34,358
Right now.

730
01:17:34,460 --> 01:17:36,587
Then come on. Let's go.

731
01:17:36,696 --> 01:17:39,597
First we gotta stop
and get supplies for the trip.

732
01:17:39,699 --> 01:17:41,667
